{"type":"text","timestamp":1778377695461,"sessionID":"ses_1f06e0781ffeCBUyFhvIAtgqsy","part":{"id":"prt_e0f921f91001TUvRPzlX3aAnai","messageID":"msg_e0f9215a8001UoBaS3h05HomD6","sessionID":"ses_1f06e0781ffeCBUyFhvIAtgqsy","type":"text","text":"The issue context line is longer than the file reader’s display limit, so I’m using `jq` to inspect the full imported issue body without touching remotes.","time":{"start":1778377695121,"end":1778377695460},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_057cff5f97dc871c0169ffe3df12c881a1b2d2178f39c5ce36","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778377696162,"sessionID":"ses_1f06e0781ffeCBUyFhvIAtgqsy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"call_vtiXaakcVfmNHawO44JsRUi5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"jq -r '.title, \"---BODY---\", .body, \"---COMMENTS---\", (.comments[]? | tostring)' __issue_context__.json","timeout":120000,"workdir":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-uberon/eval-ont-agent-uberon","description":"Prints full imported issue context"},"output":"Newly introduced crab and lobster terms violate taxon constraints\n---BODY---\nAll terms introduced in the recently merged PR #3445 (merged despite a failure of the CI check, please don’t do that…) violate taxon constraints.\r\n\r\nThis is because all those terms have the same following two assertions:\r\n\r\n> '[in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002162)' some [Astacidea](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_6712)\r\n> '[in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002162)' some [Brachyura](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_6752)\r\n\r\nThis is likely a misunderstanding of the meaning of the '[in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002162)' relation. “X '[in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002162)' some Y” means that **X is specific to the Y taxon**, i.e. X cannot exist in any other taxon that is not Y or a descendant of Y. From that meaning, it follows that a term should never have more than _one_ '[in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002162)' assertion; once a term has been asserted to be '[in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002162)' some Y1, any other assertion '[in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002162)' some Y2 will cause a contradiction, unless Y2 happens to be exactly equivalent to Y1.\r\n\r\nIf you want to state that an anatomical entity is “known to exist in a given taxon“ but without implying anything about its existence in other taxa, what you need is '[present in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002175)'.\r\n\r\nIf you want to state that an anatomical entity exists in a handful of taxa _T1_, _T2_, ... _Tn_, exclusive of all other taxa, then '[in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002162)' is the correct relation but you need to find the closest parental taxon that encompasses all the _T1_, _T2_, ... _Tn_ taxa. In the present case, [Astacidea](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_6712) and [Brachyura](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_6752) are both subtaxa of [Pleocyemata](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_6692), so the correct way to state that an anatomical entity only exists in [Astacidea](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_6712) and [Brachyura](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_6752) is\r\n\r\n> '[in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002162)' some [Pleocyemata](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_6692)\r\n\r\n---\r\nUberon contributors: Please ensure you read and understand the [guide to taxon constraints](https://oboacademy.github.io/obook/explanation/taxon-constraints-explainer) before adding/editing assertions that involve taxon constraints (any assertion that uses one of '[in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002162)', '[never in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002161)', [present in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002175)').\r\n\r\nUberon reviewers: Please do not merge a PR if the CI check failed -- at least not without asking a member of the “tech team“ first. It can happen that sometimes a CI failure is caused by “external“ factors (e.g. network issues), and in that case _and in that case only_ it may be fine to proceed with merging the PR despite the failure. But do not merge a PR with a failed check unless you know for sure it is an instance of an external problem.\n---COMMENTS---\n","metadata":{"output":"Newly introduced crab and lobster terms violate taxon constraints\n---BODY---\nAll terms introduced in the recently merged PR #3445 (merged despite a failure of the CI check, please don’t do that…) violate taxon constraints.\r\n\r\nThis is because all those terms have the same following two assertions:\r\n\r\n> '[in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002162)' some [Astacidea](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_6712)\r\n> '[in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002162)' some [Brachyura](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_6752)\r\n\r\nThis is likely a misunderstanding of the meaning of the '[in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002162)' relation. “X '[in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002162)' some Y” means that **X is specific to the Y taxon**, i.e. X cannot exist in any other taxon that is not Y or a descendant of Y. From that meaning, it follows that a term should never have more than _one_ '[in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002162)' assertion; once a term has been asserted to be '[in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002162)' some Y1, any other assertion '[in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002162)' some Y2 will cause a contradiction, unless Y2 happens to be exactly equivalent to Y1.\r\n\r\nIf you want to state that an anatomical entity is “known to exist in a given taxon“ but without implying anything about its existence in other taxa, what you need is '[present in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002175)'.\r\n\r\nIf you want to state that an anatomical entity exists in a handful of taxa _T1_, _T2_, ... _Tn_, exclusive of all other taxa, then '[in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002162)' is the correct relation but you need to find the closest parental taxon that encompasses all the _T1_, _T2_, ... _Tn_ taxa. In the present case, [Astacidea](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_6712) and [Brachyura](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_6752) are both subtaxa of [Pleocyemata](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_6692), so the correct way to state that an anatomical entity only exists in [Astacidea](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_6712) and [Brachyura](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_6752) is\r\n\r\n> '[in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002162)' some [Pleocyemata](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_6692)\r\n\r\n---\r\nUberon contributors: Please ensure you read and understand the [guide to taxon constraints](https://oboacademy.github.io/obook/explanation/taxon-constraints-explainer) before adding/editing assertions that involve taxon constraints (any assertion that uses one of '[in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002162)', '[never in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002161)', [present in taxon](http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002175)').\r\n\r\nUberon reviewers: Please do not merge a PR if the CI check failed -- at least not without asking a member of the “tech team“ first. It can happen that sometimes a CI failure is caused by “external“ factors (e.g. network issues), and in that case _and in that case only_ it may be fine to proceed with merging the PR despite the failure. But do not merge a PR with a failed check unless you know for sure it is an instance of an external problem.\n---COMMENTS---\n","exit":0,"description":"Prints full imported issue context","truncated":false},"title":"Prints full imported issue context","time":{"start":1778377696151,"end":1778377696156}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_057cff5f97dc871c0169ffe3df698881a19d9133f28f2072c8"}},"id":"prt_e0f9220e6001U4eP8fApk8MBY6","sessionID":"ses_1f06e0781ffeCBUyFhvIAtgqsy","messageID":"msg_e0f9215a8001UoBaS3h05HomD6"}}
